{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475065"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.28,0.03,0.04,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5015"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5015"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94013"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1786"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44132"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother, complaining of a rash that has been present for the past two weeks. The rash consists of papules on his thighs and axillae. It is painless and does not appear to bother him. He also has some excoriated areas over his elbow and knee creases. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His mother has a history of cold sores, and his older brother currently has cold-like symptoms. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rash is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit to hospital and perform a full septic screen with IV antibiotics","Discharge home with a course of oral valaciclovir","Discharge home with a course of oral flucloxacillin","Commence topical steroids","Reassure and review in four weeks"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe rash described in the stem is characteristic of molluscum contagiosum. This is a common, self-limiting viral infection found in young children, caused by a poxvirus. The disease is acquired through direct contact with an infected person. Children aged 2-6 years and those who are immunosuppressed are commonly affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMolluscum contagiosum typically presents as discrete, pearly, skin-coloured, smooth papules which often have a central umbilication. They can occur anywhere on the body. The most appropriate management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassure and review in four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is self-limiting and usually resolves without treatment within 6-9 months. It\u0027s important to explain this to the family and provide reassurance. No treatment is required, and the child does not need to be excluded from childcare settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no indication that this child is unwell or that the rash is a marker of sepsis. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmission to hospital\u003C/strong\u003E with a full septic screen and IV antibiotics is not warranted and would be an overreaction to this benign condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral valaciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if herpes simplex virus (HSV) or varicella-zoster virus (VZV) infection was suspected. However, this is unlikely given the rash\u0027s typical appearance of molluscum contagiosum and the fact that the child is otherwise well. The rash is also not in a distribution typical of shingles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was secondary bacterial infection of the affected areas, but there is no evidence of this in the given scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not beneficial for molluscum contagiosum. However, they might be considered for the excoriated areas on his elbow and knee creases, which could be indicative of eczema. This would be a separate issue from the molluscum contagiosum and could be addressed during the follow-up visit if needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Molluscum contagiosum is a common, self-limiting viral infection in young children that typically resolves without treatment within 6-9 months.","Molluscum contagiosum presents as discrete, pearly, skin-coloured, smooth papules often with a central umbilication.","No treatment or exclusion from childcare is required for molluscum contagiosum, but patient education and follow-up are important."],"references":["Kliegman, Robert. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. Edition 21. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94013"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19361"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19361"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"i